(Decision
    "Arca is the workspace's content-addressed archive component, a parallel to the Nix store but fundamentally different. The Nix store is addressed by the hash of the derivation recipe; Arca is addressed by the hash of the content itself. Arca holds any data that doesn't fit in sema's record shape — forge build outputs, user attachments, documents, anything blob-shaped. Triad-shaped like every component."
    "Arca is the archive component and it's a little bit of a parallel to the Nix store, but it's different in many ways. And the first, most important way in which it's different is that it is absolutely content address, whereas the nix daemon is, the Nix store, I mean, is not content addressed. The Nix store is addressed by the hash of the derivation recipe for building it … So it's also going to be a triad component style. All of my components are going to be triad components."
    "Framing Arca during the lojix daemon-mesh proposal discussion as the content-addressed substrate that would carry cross-node artifacts (Horizon projections, deploy plans, generated Nix inputs)."
    Maximum
    2026-05-17T13:30:00Z)

(Constraint
    "Nothing writes to the Arca store except the Arca daemon. The store directory is not writable by ordinary processes. This is the load-bearing TOCTOU-protection invariant: the Arca daemon computes the content hash of exactly what it moves into the store; no other writer can inject content under a hash they did not deposit through the daemon's staging path."
    "Anything should write, nothing should write to the Arca store except Arca."
    "Stating the write-authority invariant during the Arca brainstorm; Arca-daemon is the only writer, all other writers deposit through staging and Arca-daemon computes the hash."
    Maximum
    2026-05-17T13:30:00Z)

(Decision
    "Arca lives at /arca on the root filesystem with a flat layout: /arca/<hash> per entry. No multi-segment hash-prefix sharding like the Nix store does. The store path is the canonical identifier; the Arca daemon plus sema database mediate any metadata-by-name lookup."
    "we don't need a complicated file path like the Nix store. It's just on the root file system slash Arca, A-R-C-A slash, and then the hash."
    "Stating the on-disk path convention during the Arca brainstorm. Diverges from the prior `~/.arca/<store-name>/<hash>` framing in the existing arca repo's skeleton ARCH; /arca system root is the corrected direction (reports/system-specialist/139 carries the canonical decision including the base32 prefix-length policy)."
    Maximum
    2026-05-17T13:30:00Z)

(Decision
    "Sema is the source of truth for everything about an Arca-stored file beyond its bytes — filename, content type, owner, capability grants, references from other records, GC reachability. The on-disk store is just the content; sema carries the meaning. When the workspace eventually has full sema-on-sema (the eventual Criome), this distinction collapses; today Arca exists because today's sema can't hold blob-shaped data."
    "the real source of truth or important reference for all of the files in the ARCA store, which is managed by the ARCA daemon, is going to be held in the ARCA SEMA database engine, in the SEMA database, which is interacted with with the SEMA engine in ARCA."
    "Stating the metadata-source-of-truth direction; sema records describe the file, Arca holds the bytes. Matches the existing arca repo's ARCHITECTURE.md §'Role in the sema-ecosystem' framing."
    Maximum
    2026-05-17T13:30:00Z)

(Principle
    "Arca should be a fairly privileged daemon — there is nothing especially dangerous about it — but not absolutely privileged. It should not have ambient access to system private keys (e.g. operator SSH private keys). The privilege boundary is 'can ingest and serve content', not 'can read anything on the system'."
    "Arca should basically be a pretty privileged daemon because there's nothing really dangerous about it. And, well, actually that's not true. It shouldn't be able to read private keys and stuff easily. So if we give it a path to a private key, then it should not be able to actually read it. Or, you know, I mean, not like system private keys, like the system SSH key and so on. So it should not be an absolute privileged daemon, but it should absolutely not be writable by pretty much anything except root, which actually would be misbehavior by the system."
    "Setting the privilege envelope during the Arca brainstorm; carve-out for private-key paths explicitly excluded from Arca's reachable surface."
    Maximum
    2026-05-17T13:30:00Z)

(Principle
    "File-path readability matters because hashes are LLM-expensive — they tokenize as roughly one token per character. Long content-addressed paths in agent context, logs, references, and reports become significant cost. The shortest reliable identifier is the right design target, balanced against collision risk. (Specific hash-prefix length policy lives in reports/system-specialist/139's canonical Arca decisions.)"
    "I really want to, like, debate that hard because these file paths, when they end up in things like, well, anywhere really, but especially LLM context, they become extremely costly because hashes are not recognizable tokens. They're not words or anything in natural language, so they end up costing, like, a full byte per character, which is very inefficient."
    "Articulating the LLM-cost dimension of identifier design during the Arca brainstorm; drove the hash-prefix-length debate that settled in reports/system-specialist/139 with the base32 prefix floor (10-12 chars), not the original 3-character proposal nor my counter-proposal of fixed 16-hex."
    Medium
    2026-05-17T13:30:00Z)
